George Fletcher said:

@Kathleen I don’t see the proposal by Pieter and Yaroslav as saying OAuth isn’t useful but rather that OAuth is just one of the building blocks needed in a complete solution.

OAuth is one building block in one of the potential architectures for a complete solution.  I've seen at least 5 different potential architecture concepts. An honest intellectual discussion would look at the different architectures/frameworks that are evolving in this field, discuss the different components for each framework, and come to an educated guess about which parts of the framework are in need of standardization, versus which parts of the framework are perfectly fine with interoperability software.

@stephen - the firt step is to write down what we can do - this is what https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-klrc-aiagent-auth/ does.
It surfaced gaps that we can work on.
We also need to distinguish between capability that exists in specs and the operational complexity of some of the extreme "fine grained authorization" use cases. The problem is less the protocols and more the operational complexity in my experience.

George Fletcher said:

@Day “delegation of authority” is a really big problem… however I’m not sure everyone would agree that’s the problem they want to solve

I'm keen to better understand what it is beyond this.
